inputs_used.system_design:
Objectives: Build a scalable, secure, SEO-friendly website with modern UX, multi-environment deployment (dev/staging/prod), and strong observability. Support public marketing pages, authenticated user area (dashboard/profile), content management (blog/pages), search, notifications, and optional commerce add-ons.

High-Level Architecture:
- Client Layer: Responsive web app with server-side rendering (SSR) for SEO-critical pages; client-side hydration for interactivity. Static assets served via CDN.
- Edge/CDN: Global CDN for caching HTML (SSR), images, CSS/JS, and applying security headers. Image optimization at the edge when possible.
- Web Tier: Next.js app servers behind a load balancer. Uses incremental static regeneration for content-heavy pages and SSR for dynamic routes.
- API Layer: RESTful services (modular monolith at start; microservices-ready). Services: Auth, User, Content, Media, Search, Notification. API gateway handles routing, rate limiting, and centralized auth.
- Data Layer: PostgreSQL (primary OLTP), Redis (cache/session/ratelimit), OpenSearch/Elasticsearch (full-text search), Object Storage (S3-compatible) for media.
- Integration Layer: Email provider (transactional and marketing), optional payments (Stripe), third-party analytics.
- Observability: Centralized logging (ELK/OpenSearch), metrics (Prometheus), tracing (OpenTelemetry), APM (Datadog/New Relic). Feature flags (LaunchDarkly or OpenFeature).
- Security: OIDC/OAuth2, JWT access tokens + short-lived sessions, CSRF protection for forms, input validation, rate limiting, WAF at CDN, secrets manager, least-privilege IAM, periodic security scans.
- CI/CD & Environments: Git-based workflow, PR checks, automated testing, container builds, deploy to staging, blue/green or canary to prod. Infrastructure as Code (Terraform).

Core Services & Responsibilities:
- Auth Service: OIDC/OAuth2, user sessions, roles/permissions, passwordless/email magic links optional.
- User Service: Profiles, preferences, account settings.
- Content Service: Pages, posts, categories/tags, comments, drafts/publish workflow, versioning.
- Media Service: Uploads, processing (thumbnails), CDN delivery.
- Search Service: Indexing content/users, autosuggest, filters.
- Notification Service: Email, in-app notifications; queue-based delivery.
- Admin/CMS UI: Role-based access, content editing, media library, audit trails.

Data Flows:
- Content authoring -> CMS -> Content Service -> DB + Search Index -> Next.js ISR updates -> CDN cache purge.
- User requests -> CDN -> Next.js SSR -> API Gateway -> respective services -> DB/cache -> response -> cached where appropriate.

Scalability & Resilience:
- Horizontal scaling of web/API pods; DB vertical scaling + read replicas; Redis cluster for cache; search nodes with replication. Circuit breakers and retries; graceful degradation (serve cached content).

Database Design (Conceptual Schema):
- Users(id, email, password_hash/null for SSO, status, created_at)
- Roles(id, name); UserRoles(user_id, role_id)
- Permissions(id, key); RolePermissions(role_id, permission_id)
- Profiles(user_id PK/FK, display_name, avatar_url, bio, locale, timezone)
- Sessions(id, user_id, refresh_token_hash, expires_at, device_info)
- Content(id, type ENUM(page|post), title, slug, body_richtext, excerpt, author_id, status ENUM(draft|scheduled|published|archived), published_at, updated_at, version)
- Categories(id, name, slug); Tags(id, name, slug)
- ContentCategories(content_id, category_id); ContentTags(content_id, tag_id)
- Comments(id, content_id, user_id/null, body, status ENUM(pending|approved|rejected), parent_comment_id nullable)
- MediaAssets(id, owner_user_id, storage_key, mime_type, width, height, alt_text, created_at)
- Notifications(id, user_id, type, payload JSONB, status ENUM(pending|sent|failed), channel ENUM(email|in_app), created_at)
- AuditLogs(id, actor_user_id, action, target_type, target_id, metadata JSONB, created_at)
- Settings(id, key, value JSONB)
- Optional Commerce: Products, Orders, OrderItems, Payments (if needed later)
Indexes: email unique, slug unique per type, composite indexes on (content.status, published_at), full-text indexes via OpenSearch, foreign keys with cascading rules.

Caching Strategy:
- CDN for static assets and SSR HTML for public pages (short TTL + stale-while-revalidate).
- Redis: hot content, user session, rate limits, feature flags cache; per-route cache for expensive queries.

Security & Compliance:
- OWASP top 10 mitigations, TLS everywhere, secure cookies, CSP, HSTS, subresource integrity, encryption at rest, GDPR-ready data lifecycle (consent, export/delete), audit logging.

Migration & Data Governance:
- Prisma/TypeORM migrations; seed scripts for dev; versioned schema; backup/restore tested; PII minimization; data retention policies.

inputs_used.prompt:
Create a production-ready Python script named auto_complex_dataset_analysis.py that automatically analyzes a dataset (default: complex.csv) and attempts to solve the data problem by performing the following:

1) Command-line interface:
   - Arguments:
     --data_path (default: "complex.csv")
     --target (optional): name of the target column; if omitted, the script will do unsupervised analysis.
     --max_categories (default: 50) threshold beyond which categorical features are treated as high-cardinality.
     --test_size (default: 0.2)
     --random_state (default: 42)
     --output_dir (default: "code/complex_dataset_analysis")
   - Print helpful usage and provide clear logging to console and file.

2) Directory structure and outputs (created if not present):
   - {output_dir}/reports/
     * EDA.md: human-readable summary of dataset, schema, missing values, duplicates, constant columns, and notable findings.
     * profile.json: machine-readable profiling information (counts, dtypes, missing stats, cardinality, anomalies).
     * model_metrics.json: classification/regression metrics (if target provided).
     * clustering_summary.json: silhouette scores and chosen k (if no target provided).
     * kmeans_silhouette_scores.json: per-k scores.
     * run.log: log file.
   - {output_dir}/plots/
     * correlation_heatmap.png
     * pca_scatter.png (if unsupervised or for exploratory purposes)
     * feature_importance.png (if applicable)
   - {output_dir}/artifacts/
     * best_model.joblib (if target provided)
     * preprocessor.joblib
     * feature_importance.csv

3) Data loading and profiling:
   - Load CSV with pandas, infer dtypes, and handle common issues (bad lines, encoding errors; fall back to utf-8-sig and engine='python' if needed).
   - Basic profile: shape, columns, memory usage, dtypes, missing values per column, unique counts.
   - Quality checks: detect duplicates, constant columns, mixed-type columns, high-cardinality categoricals, potential date columns, and outliers (IQR method for numeric columns; report flagged rows count per column).
   - Save profile.json and EDA.md summarizing findings.

4) Preprocessing pipeline using scikit-learn:
   - Separate features X and target y if target provided; else X is all columns.
   - Identify numeric and categorical columns.
   - Numeric: SimpleImputer(strategy='median') + StandardScaler.
   - Categorical: SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent') + OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse=False).
   - ColumnTransformer combining both; export to preprocessor.joblib.

5) Correlation analysis:
   - Compute correlation matrix for numeric features; save heatmap as correlation_heatmap.png.

6) Supervised learning (if --target provided):
   - Determine task type automatically:
     * If y is numeric and number of unique values > 15, treat as regression.
     * If y is numeric with unique values <= 15 or y is non-numeric/categorical, treat as classification.
   - Train/test split using test_size and random_state.
   - Build pipelines for baseline models:
     * Classification: LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000), RandomForestClassifier.
     * Regression: LinearRegression, RandomForestRegressor.
   - Perform cross-validation (e.g., 5-fold) to estimate performance; evaluate on test set.
   - Metrics:
     * Classification: accuracy, f1 (macro), precision (macro), recall (macro), ROC-AUC (if binary); confusion matrix saved as image if feasible.
     * Regression: MAE, MSE, RMSE, R2.
   - Select best model by primary metric (classification: f1_macro; regression: R2). Save best_model.joblib and model_metrics.json.
   - Compute feature importance (from RandomForest model if available; otherwise permutation importance); save feature_importance.csv and feature_importance.png.

7) Unsupervised analysis (if --target not provided):
   - PCA on numeric features (after preprocessing; reduce to 2 components for plotting). Save pca_scatter.png colored by KMeans clusters (if clustering performed).
   - KMeans clustering with k in [2..min(10, n_samples-1)], evaluate silhouette score for each k; choose best k; save clustering_summary.json and kmeans_silhouette_scores.json; output cluster assignments to a CSV file in artifacts (e.g., clusters.csv).

8) Robustness and logging:
   - Use logging module to log to console and file (run.log) with INFO level, include timestamps.
   - Gracefully handle errors with informative messages and continue where possible (e.g., plotting correlation only for numeric features; skip ROC-AUC if multiclass and not supported without probability estimates).
   - Ensure all directories exist; catch exceptions and write them to run.log.

9) Code quality and usability:
   - Clear, modular functions: load_data(), profile_data(), build_preprocessor(), supervised_workflow(), unsupervised_workflow(), save_reports_and_plots().
   - Main guard if __name__ == "__main__": parse args and run appropriate workflow.
   - Include docstrings and comments for maintainability.

10) Extra implementation details:
   - When saving images, use tight_layout and dpi=150.
   - For large datasets, clip plotting data if necessary to avoid memory issues (e.g., sample up to 50k rows for PCA scatter plot).
   - When encoding categoricals, drop columns exceeding max_categories if they are categorical and non-numeric, but make a note in EDA.md and profile.json.
   - After training, print and log a concise summary of results and paths to generated artifacts.

Assume Python 3.9+ and standard ML stack availability (pandas, numpy, scikit-learn, seaborn, matplotlib, joblib). If an optional dependency is not available, catch and warn. The script must run end-to-end from the command line and produce the described outputs. Save the file to the folder code/complex_dataset_analysis.

Write a Python script named quantum_computing.py that does the following:

1) Overview and reproducibility:
- Deterministic run with random.seed(42).
- Print a clear summary of constraints and final results.
- Include a top comment: "Generated using Grok-3 LLM".

2) Quantum amplitude and probability definitions:
- Assume an n-qubit product state parameterized by angles thetas[i] and phases phis[i].
- Single-qubit amplitudes:
  * For bit b_i = 0: a_i = cos(theta_i)
  * For bit b_i = 1: a_i = e^{i * phi_i} * sin(theta_i)
- State amplitude for a bitstring b is the product of the corresponding a_i across all qubits.
- Probability(b) = |amplitude(b)|^2.

3) Constraints for optimization (specific and hard-coded):
- N = 8 qubits.
- Hamming weight K = 3 (exactly 3 ones).
- Fixed bits: index 0 must be 1, index 7 must be 0.
- No adjacent ones (for all i, not both b[i] and b[i+1] equal 1).
- Use penalties to enforce constraints in an energy function.

4) Parameters:
- thetas = [0.35, 0.60, 0.45, 0.80, 0.20, 0.55, 0.70, 0.30]
- phis   = [0.00, 0.50, 1.00, -0.30, 0.80, -1.20, 0.20, -0.70]
- Penalty weight P = 2.0
- Target bitstring for reporting the probability of a certain amplitude: "10100100" (must use this exact string, even if it violates constraints; we just report its amplitude and probability.)

5) Simulated annealing to maximize probability under constraints:
- Define energy(bitstring) = -probability(bitstring) + P * violations(bitstring), where violations() counts:
  * Hamming weight != K (add abs(weight - K) to violation count)
  * Fixed bits mismatches (add 1 per mismatch)
  * Adjacent ones count (each adjacent-one pair adds 1)
- Initialize a valid or near-valid bitstring respecting fixed bits and K (exactly K ones, but adjacency may initially be violated). If necessary, allow initial violations and rely on penalties to improve.
- Proposal move that preserves Hamming weight and fixed-bit constraints: choose i from indices where b[i]==1 and not fixed to 1; choose j from indices where b[j]==0 and not fixed to 0; set b[i]=0, b[j]=1.
- Metropolis acceptance: accept if ΔE <= 0 else accept with probability exp(-ΔE/T).
- Temperature schedule: T0 = 1.0; linearly cool to T_final = 1e-3 over max_iters = 20000 iterations.
- Track the best candidate seen (lowest energy). Also track the best feasible candidate (violations==0) separately.

6) Output:
- Print constraint summary.
- Compute and print amplitude and probability for the target bitstring "10100100".
- Print the best result found by SA: the bitstring, amplitude (complex), probability (float), energy, and whether constraints are satisfied (violations==0), along with counts of violations.
- If a fully feasible best candidate was found, report it explicitly; otherwise, report the best overall and note remaining violations.

7) Code structure:
- Functions:
  * bits_to_str(bits)
  * str_to_bits(s)
  * amplitude(bits, thetas, phis)
  * probability(bits, thetas, phis)
  * count_violations(bits, K, fixed, no_adjacent=True) -> (violation_count, detail_dict)
  * energy(bits)
  * propose_move(bits, fixed, K)
  * simulated_annealing(...)
- Main: set up parameters, run SA, and print results.

Please produce a single, self-contained Python file that adheres strictly to the above specification and prints the requested outputs.
